title: Bug: Converting quantized Keras models to TFLite
body:
### System information

-   **Have I written custom code (as opposed to using a stock example script
    provided in TensorFlow)**: Yes
-   **OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04)**: Windows 10
-   **TensorFlow installed from (source or binary)**: binary
-   **TensorFlow version (use command below)**: 2.3.1
-   **Python version**: 3.8.2

### Describe the problem
Appears to be a bug when trying to convert quantized Keras models to TFLite. Goal is to be able to generate TFLite models using quantized TFHub models.

### Source code / logs
Source Code
import tensorflow as tf
import tensorflow_hub as hub

input_val = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(320,320,3), dtype=tf.uint8)
module = hub.KerasLayer('https://tfhub.dev/tensorflow/ssd_mobilenet_v2/fpnlite_320x320/1')(input_val)
model = tf.keras.models.Model(inputs=[input_val], outputs=[module])
model.summary()
converter = tf.lite.TFLiteConverter.from_keras_model(model)
model_out = converter.convert()

Error

line 216, in toco_convert_protos
    raise ConverterError(str(e))

comments:
Hey. 

The hub modules for SSD MobileNet might not be directly convertible to TensorFlow Lite. The idea here is to first convert it to something that compatible with the current opset of TensorFlow Lite. This is detailed [here](https://github.com/tensorflow/models/blob/master/research/object_detection/g3doc/running_on_mobile_tf2.md). 

However, [here's a repository](https://github.com/sayakpaul/E2E-Object-Detection-in-TFLite) that would show you an end-to-end example of converting an SSD MobileNet to TFLite and running inference with it. I hope you'd find it useful.

It doesn't appear to be an issue with any operations as if we create a single output ssd model where the two outputs are concatenated together, we can use tf.keras.Sequential with the model and the TFLiteConverter will work. Also using a float version of the model does not lead to any issues. It appears to be an issue with the datatypes, where it is unable to handle uint8 tensors as seen with the error  (tensor<?x320x320x3x!tf.quint8>) -> tensor<?x320x320x3xui8> with the tf.Identity operation. I also was testing with the https://tfhub.dev/tensorflow/ssd_mobilenet_v2/2 model which I know has all of the supported ops in TFLite, it still gives the error of "requires all operands and results to have compatible element types" which leads me back to the issue with datatype conversion in the TFLiteConverter.

Thanks though for the links, I'll take a look to see if there could be an unsupported op with the fpnlite version of the SSD

@msquigle It appears that your input is uint8, which is supported only in quantization mode. As a workaround, you can do the following things. If you want to do post training quantization, please follow the [guideline](https://www.tensorflow.org/lite/performance/post_training_quantization). Thank you!

```python
float_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(320, 320, 3), dtype=tf.float32)
uint8_input = tf.cast(float_input, dtype=tf.uint8)
module = hub.KerasLayer('https://tfhub.dev/tensorflow/ssd_mobilenet_v2/fpnlite_320x320/1')(uint8_input)
model = tf.keras.models.Model(inputs=[float_input], outputs=[module])
model.summary()
model.save("/tmp/ssd_mobilenet_v2")
converter = tf.lite.TFLiteConverter.from_keras_model(model)
model_out = converter.convert()
```

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/lite/python/lite.py#L551-L568

title: Common location for portable bash helper functions / aliases
body:
@tensorflow/micro

PR #46011 fixes the use of `md5sum` to be compatible with a Mac. We are already using `md5sum` in additional places too.

While we should get #46011 merged, it would be better to have a common location for these helper functions / aliases.

I can imagine collecting these into a common helper script (for example `micro/tools/bash_helpers.sh`) and have something like:

```bash

UNAME_S=`uname -s`

if [ UNAME_S == Linux]; then
  alias tflm_md5sum='md5sum'
else if [ UNAME_S == Darwin ]; then
  alias tflm_md5sum='md5 -r'
fi

```

We would then need to change the different download scripts to determine the directory in which the script lives, something like: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/59f5abfbc8dc5559c361f80f4fa4a006db825e40/tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/ci_build/test_bluepill.sh#L21-L23

and then have
```bash
source tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/bash_helper.sh
```
